The history of fighting in hockey

As with all sports, the origins of the sport and rules formed gradually through a natural evolution as people play the game.

Hockey is a fast, graceful, but brutally violent sport. The speed that you can get on skates combined with newer rules allowing for forward passes and the neutral zone made the neutral zone a lot more violent. Defenders didn’t allow people through the neutral zone without taking a punishment. Tempers flared and the enforcer class was born to try to check the violent play against the more skilled players.

The lack of officiating and rules made fighting a part of the game as players took matters into their own hands. A quality goon would make you think twice about taking a shot at the top line center.

As the NHL was expanding through the US in the late 70s and 80s, fights sky rocketed. People loved the fights at the time. Ever heard the expression “I watch hockey for the fights?” The peak of fights per game was during this time.

Teams with superstars like Gretzky would have their goons fight to clear space for the talent to move. Originally, the penalty for fighting would remove both pugilists from the ice creating a 4-on-4 allowing Gretzky to score at will with plenty of open ice. In the mid eighties a rule change was made where both players were removed, but they had to be replaced on the ice, keeping it a 5-on-5. [1]

More recently, fights have been on the decline:

The reasons for this are many fold. Referees have taken better control of the game. More skill players are emerging. In order to counter a speedy player with good hands teams do not have the space to hold onto a goon. Fans don’t like it as much as they used to. Now that the sport is at least a couple of decades old in most markets, the fans are educated on the sport enough to not just watch it for the fights (which really do suck, it’s like two grown men spinning in a circle until they’re taken to the box).

Instigator rules have also been put in place to further punish a guy that starts the fight, they add an additional minor penalty to the 5 for fighting and sometimes can be an additional major and match penalty. This season was especially strange with it’s implementation as the added minor was often arbitrary making teams very wary about letting their guys fight since they might take an additional penalty as a result.

A few people have looked at the results of fights. It turns out there might be a momentum swing from a fight, but it’s entirely unpredictable to whom the swing favors. Realizing that, also, you might as well just play out the game rather than risk losing worse.[2]

Back to the original question

There were a lot of fights in hockey because it was part of the rules. People liked it, until they didn’t.

Some people cling to the stupid “tradition” of it, but in the end, fights are on the way out.

